question.description:
[*C. elegans*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caenorhabditis_elegans) is a roundworm that's about 1 millimeter in length. It's often used as a model organism to study neurology due to the extreme simplicity of its nervous system, with only [302 neurons](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK116086/) and 56 glial cells. Its nervous system was [first described](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4360118/) in 1986, yet as of June 2025 still unable to be modeled, which is a persistent .&#x20;

The [OpenWorm](https://openworm.org/) project for example has worked since 2011 as an open-source collaboration to model *C. elegans*, which has been a tough slog. According to Wired:&#x20;

> If OpenWorm can manage this, it would be the first virtual animal‚Äîand an embodiment of all our knowledge not only about *C. elegans*, which is one of the most-studied animals in science, but about how brains interact with the world to produce behavior: the ‚Äúholy grail,‚Äù as OpenWorm puts it, of systems biology.

> Unfortunately, they haven‚Äôt managed it. The simulation on my laptop takes data culled from experiments done with living worms and translates it into a computational framework called c302, which then drives the simulated musculature of a *C. elegans* worm in a fluid dynamic environment‚Äîall in all, a simulation of how a worm squiggles forward in a flat plate of goo. It takes about 10 hours of compute time to generate five seconds of this behavior.

Convergent Research, a non-profit funder of scientific research, has put together a Gap Map of bottlenecks slowing scientific advancement. Big on the Gap Map is [Digital Replicas of the Whole Brain of a Model Organism](https://www.gap-map.org/capabilities/digital-replicas-of-the-whole-brain-of-a-model-organism/). An eventual goal is of course understanding the [human brain](https://www.gap-map.org/fields/neuroscience/), especially to overcome diseases such as Alzheimer's. Cracking the code of C. elegans would therefore be an important first step.&#x20;

See Also

* MIT News: [Modeling complex behavior with a simple organism](https://news.mit.edu/2025/modeling-complex-behavior-steven-flavell-0121) | By studying the roundworm C. elegans, neuroscientist Steven Flavell explores how neural circuits give rise to behavior.
* Science Advances: [Nervous system‚Äìwide analysis of all *C. elegans* cadherins reveals neuron-specific functions across multiple anatomical scales](https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.ads2852)
* Nature Computational Science: [A simulated *C. elegans* with biophysically detailed neurons and muscle dynamics](https://www.nature.com/articles/s43588-024-00740-2)

question.fine_print:
A closed-loop simulated environment requires that the virtual worm's motor commands change its body, which alters the sensory inputs it then receives (touch, temperature, etc.), which then feeds back into or triggers its next motor commands, and so on. Kinematic replay of previously-recorded behavior does not count.&#x20;

For a given test to count, no manual overriding of behavior should occur. Any weights or parameters must be set before the test.

90% accuracy means that for each canonical behavior tested, the software must achieve ‚â•90% event-level accuracy when compared to *C. elegan*s wild-type worms, using the accepted quantitative metrics at the time of the test (e.g., propulsion and muscle contraction), possibly according to [Wormbase](https://wormbase.org/) or [The Caenorhabditis Natural Diversity Resource](https://caendr.org/).

The neural model must contain a representation of every neuron and synaptic connection of the simulated *C. elegan*s. Simplifications of certain neural dynamics may be acceptable if biologically justified, as determined by Metaculus.&#x20;

For example, at the end of trading on August 22, 2025, the Technology sector had a Market Weight of 30.00% according to Yahoo Finance and the Communication Services sector had a Market Weight of 9.76%. Thus, the resolution value on that day would have been 39.76%.&#x20;

The primary source for this question will be [Yahoo Finance](https://finance.yahoo.com/sectors/) but Metaculus may incorporate other sources in the resolution of this question. Metaculus will rely on the best available information to determine the final value.

If Yahoo Finance, or other sources list a new sector not listed on August 23, 2025, Metaculus will judge whether the new sector is a subsection of "Technology" or "Communication Services" that has been split off. If Metaculus determines that this has occurred, it will additionally consider the new sections in the resolution of this question.

An example of an absolute exclusion that would count for purposes of this question is the one introduced in 2025 by Berkley Insurance Co. ([Law 360](https://www.hunton.com/insights/publications/how-insurance-policies-are-adapting-to-ai-risk), [National Law Review](https://natlawreview.com/article/continued-proliferation-ai-exclusions))

A broad, absolute exclusion of AI means the insurance company explicitly excludes or denies coverage for damages arising from AI systems that lack human override capabilities (i.e, the ability for humans to intervene in or alter AI system decisions before implementation), or does so via a blanket AI exclusion that clearly applies to such systems as a subset of a wider group. Thus, sector-specific exclusions (e.g., a hypothetical scenario in which USAA announces it will explicitly exclude coverage vehicles operating autonomously but remains silent on its other insurance lines) do not qualify unless they establish a general principle applicable across the company's entire portfolio of policy types.

This question asks whether insurers broadly exclude coverage in their standard policies for AI systems lacking human override capabilities. Thus, if the insurance company sells [riders](https://www.investopedia.com/terms/r/rider.asp) or add-ons to allow coverage of AI lacking human oversight, it will still count for purposes of this question.&#x20;

